ED model 1

David Henderson

28, January, 2019

Introduction

ED model. Same drill as with social care models but dependent variable is attendance at A & E in the 6 months after end of financial year and adding social care in as an independent variable. I’m doing this for the whole cohort again but without councils or health boards - they have little effect.

Fit the model to all years

Formula for this model: glm(usc_six ~ sex*age_grp + simd*meds_grp + age_grp*meds_grp + scs_flag*age_grp + dod_six*age_grp + usc_flag + care_home

start <- Sys.time()

#Create a function for the model
ed_model <- function(my_df){
  glm(ed_six ~                                  #The formula for the model
        sex*age_grp + 
        simd*meds_grp +
        age_grp*meds_grp +
        scs_flag*age_grp +
        dod_six*age_grp +
        usc_flag +
        care_home, 
      family = binomial(),                      #Logistic regression
      data = my_df)                             #identify which data to use
  }
 

ed_model_1 <- 
  thesis_usc %>%  #Main dataframe
  group_by(year) %>% 
  #Nest data for each year
  nest(.key = "year_data") %>% 
  #Create model column using above function
  mutate(mod_var = map(year_data, ed_model),
         #Tidy coefficients using broom::tidy into a column
         tidy_var = map(mod_var, tidy), 
         #compute AMEs and add as a column
         marginals = map2(mod_var, year_data, ~margins_summary(.x, data = .y))) 

print(Sys.time()-start)
save(ed_model_1, file = "Research/created_objects/models/ed_model_1.rds")

Note: Time difference = 8.6 hrs

Model fit

Fit statistics

Create new list column to model object with fit statistics using broom::glance

ed_model_1 %<>% 
  mutate(glance_var = map(mod_var, glance))

Now I need to mannually calcluate McFadden’s pseudo \(R^{2}\) which has the formula:

\[R^{2}_{McFadden} = 1 - \frac {ln(LM_{1})}{ln(LM_{0})} \]

Where, \(ln(LM_{1})\) is the log likelihood value for the fitted model and \(ln(LM_{0})\) is the log likelihood for the null model with only an intercept as a predictor.

Calculate the pseudo \(R^2\), then rearrange variable order whilst dropping unwanted variables from glance - Print this out - will need reported.

ed_model_1 %>%
  #unnest the list column of fit stats
  unnest(glance_var, .drop = TRUE) %>%
  arrange(year) %>% 
  #Calculate McFadden's pseudo R2
  mutate(pseud_r2 = 1 - (logLik / (null.deviance / -2)),  
         year = case_when(!!!year_char)) %>% 
  #Add a variable showing logLik of null model
  mutate(null.logLik = null.deviance / -2) %>%
  #Rearrange and drop variables
  select(year, pseud_r2, deviance, logLik, df.residual, 
         null.deviance, null.logLik,  df.null) %>%
  #Round everything to 3 decimal places
  round_df(dig = 3)-> gof_tab

gof_tab
#my_datatable(gof_tab)

Anything with pseudo \(R^2\) 0.2-0.4 is considered a very good fit. I’d day these models aren’t so good although given the residual plots in the USC and Admission models I’m not going to discount them yet.

Residual assessment

Not excpecting normally distributed residuals or constant variance as I am using a non-linear model. However, can have a look at the deviance residual to see if indiviudal points are not well fitted.

I use augment() from broom to find values then plot the standardised residuals to see how many exceed 3 standard deviations.

I won’t be formally reporting this (hence non-tidied plot) but need to have a look and will probably mention it whilst discussing results. I am using 2015/16 as a reference year here as it had the poorest fit

#Add fitted values (and associated stats) to every observation
ed_model_1 %<>% 
  mutate(aug_var = map(mod_var, augment))
ed_model_1 %>%
  filter(year == ymd(20160331)) %>% 
  unnest(.$aug_var) %>% 
  mutate(index = 1:n())-> aug_data_1112

aug_data_1112 %>% 
  ggplot(aes(index, .std.resid, colour = ed_six)) +
  geom_point() +
  geom_hline(yintercept = 3) +
  scale_colour_ptol() +
  theme(axis.text.x = element_blank()) + #supress index for SDC
  labs(title = "Standardised residuals", 
       subtitle = "2015/16",
       colour = "", 
       x = "")

As with USC and Admission models the residuals look good. Really good in fact…..

Marginal effects

Now to look at AMEs

ed_model_1 %>%  
  unnest(marginals) %>% 
  round_df(dig = 3) %>% 
  arrange(year, AME) %>% 
  mutate(order = row_number())-> usc_marginal
  

#Tidy up labels
prefixes <- c("sex")
usc_marginal$factor <- prefix_strip(usc_marginal$factor, prefixes)
usc_marginal$factor <- prefix_replace(usc_marginal$factor, "Meds_grp",
                                       "Meds: ")
usc_marginal$factor <- prefix_replace(usc_marginal$factor, 
                                       "Age_grp", "Age: ")
usc_marginal$factor <- prefix_replace(usc_marginal$factor,
                                       "Simd", "SIMD Decile: ", 
                                       toTitle = FALSE)
usc_marginal$factor <- prefix_replace(usc_marginal$factor,
                                       "scs_flag", "")
usc_marginal$factor <- prefix_replace(usc_marginal$factor,
                                       "dod_six", "")
usc_marginal$factor <- prefix_replace(usc_marginal$factor,
                                       "usc_flag", "")
usc_marginal$factor <- prefix_replace(usc_marginal$factor,
                                       "care_home", "")

Plot marginal effects

Plot the table

usc_marginal %>% 
  ggplot(aes(order, AME, ymin = lower, ymax = upper)) +
  geom_hline(yintercept = 0, colour = "#AAAAAA") +
  geom_pointrange() +
  facet_wrap(~year, labeller = as_labeller(year_labels), scales = "free") +
  scale_y_continuous(limits = c(-0.2, 0.3),
                     breaks = scales::pretty_breaks()) +

  coord_flip() +
  labs(x = "",
       y= "Average Partial Effect", 
       title = "Influence of variables on having an A & E attendance",
       subtitle = "Average Partial Effects ordered high to low by year",
       caption = "Reference group Age: 65-69\nReference group Meds: 0-2 medicines") -> ed_model_1_AME_plot

Plot SIMD

SIMD id different from the rest as it is modelled as a continuous variable. I’m going to produce a separate plot for it to make interpretation easier.

ed_model_1 %<>% 
  mutate(cplot_simd = map2(mod_var, year_data,
                           ~cplot(.x, data = .y, x = "simd", draw=FALSE)))
ed_model_1 %>% 
  filter(year == ymd(20140331)) %>% 
  unnest(cplot_simd) %>%
  ggplot(aes(x = xvals)) +
  geom_line(aes(y = yvals)) +
  geom_line(aes(y = upper), linetype = 2) +
  geom_line(aes(y = lower), linetype = 2) +
  scale_x_continuous(breaks = scales::pretty_breaks(n = 10)) +
  scale_y_continuous(breaks = scales::pretty_breaks(),
                     limits = c(0, 0.1)) +
  labs(title = "Conditional effect of SIMD Decile on A & E attendance",
       subtitle = "2013/14",
       x = "SIMD Decile",
       y = "Predicted value") -> ed_model_1_simd_plot
